body:
I'm working on a design in Chisel that has a module which is instantiated many times, and should be deduped. However, after making it `Public`, I see that it doesn't dedup anymore. I'm not sure if this is the desired behavior, since I didn't see anything about it in [the FIRRTL Spec](https://github.com/chipsalliance/firrtl-spec).

You can recreate this behavior with the following `scala-cli` snippet, which uses `firtool-1.122.0`:

```scala
//> using scala 2.13.16
//> using repository https://s01.oss.sonatype.org/content/repositories/snapshots
//> using dep org.chipsalliance::chisel:7.0.0-RC1+37-f8a2dec3-SNAPSHOT
//> using plugin org.chipsalliance:::chisel-plugin:7.0.0-RC1+37-f8a2dec3-SNAPSHOT
//> using options -unchecked -deprecation -language:reflectiveCalls -feature -Xcheckinit -Xfatal-warnings -Ywarn-dead-code -Ywarn-unused -Ymacro-annotations

import chisel3._

class Bar extends Module with Public with RequireAsyncReset {
  printf("foo")
}

class Foo extends Module with RequireAsyncReset {
  val bar0 = Module(new Bar)
  val bar1 = Module(new Bar)
}

object Main extends App {
  import _root_.circt.stage.ChiselStage
  println(
    ChiselStage.emitSystemVerilog(
      new Foo,
      firtoolOpts = Array("-disable-all-randomization", "-strip-debug-info", "-default-layer-specialization=enable")
    )
  )
}
```

You get the following result, with separate `Bar` and `Bar_1` modules:

```verilog
// Generated by CIRCT firtool-1.122.0

// Users can define 'PRINTF_COND' to add an extra gate to prints.
`ifndef PRINTF_COND_
  `ifdef PRINTF_COND
    `define PRINTF_COND_ (`PRINTF_COND)
  `else  // PRINTF_COND
    `define PRINTF_COND_ 1
  `endif // PRINTF_COND
`endif // not def PRINTF_COND_
module Bar(
  input clock,
        reset
);

  `ifndef SYNTHESIS
    always @(posedge clock) begin
      if ((`PRINTF_COND_) & ~reset)
        $fwrite(32'h80000002, "foo");
    end // always @(posedge)
  `endif // not def SYNTHESIS
endmodule

module Bar_1(
  input clock,
        reset
);

  `ifndef SYNTHESIS
    always @(posedge clock) begin
      if ((`PRINTF_COND_) & ~reset)
        $fwrite(32'h80000002, "foo");
    end // always @(posedge)
  `endif // not def SYNTHESIS
endmodule

module Foo(
  input clock,
        reset
);

  Bar bar0 (
    .clock (clock),
    .reset (reset)
  );
  Bar_1 bar1 (
    .clock (clock),
    .reset (reset)
  );
endmodule
```

If you remove the `with Public` from the `Bar` class, you only get a single `Bar` module in the output.

Is this the intended behavior? Is Chisel's `Definition`/`Instance` API the only way to achieve deduped `Bar`s?

